      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Braise the mutton",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{olive-oil}} of olive oil",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " in a casserole over high heat. Dust the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{mutton}} of mutton",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " chunks with flour and season. Brown in batches; remove. Soften the onion and carrot for 5 minutes. Add garlic, rosemary, bay. Return the meat. Add ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{red-wine}} of red wine",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " if using and reduce by half. Add ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{stock-beef}} of stock",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Cover and cook in a 160°C oven for 2 hours until the meat is tender and the sauce is thick. Season with ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{sea-salt-flakes}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{black-pepper}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Cool completely.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Top and bake",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 200°C (180°C fan). Spoon the cold filling into a deep pie dish. Roll the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{shortcrust-pastry}} of shortcrust pastry",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " to 4 mm thickness and lay it over the dish. Press to seal, trim, and crimp. Score the surface and cut a steam vent. Brush with beaten egg. Bake for 35-40 minutes until deeply golden.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "rows": [
            {
              "fix": "Return to the oven for 30-minute increments. Mutton can take up to 3 hours in some cases.",
              "cause": "Older animal or thicker chunks",
              "symptom": "Mutton is still tough after 2 hours"
            },
            {
              "fix": "After braising, reduce the sauce by simmering uncovered for 10 minutes before the pie is assembled.",
              "cause": "Insufficient flour for thickening, or lid was left off",
              "symptom": "Sauce is watery"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Aim for a consistent 4 mm; thinner pastry tears when draped over a full dish.",
              "cause": "Rolled too thinly",
              "symptom": "Pastry lid tears when lifted"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Brown the meat in properly hot oil, in batches, until deeply coloured. The fond from browning is the foundation of the flavour.",
              "cause": "Mutton was not browned adequately at the start",
              "symptom": "Flavour lacks depth"
            }
          ]
        },
        "content": []
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Mutton pie sits beside steak and kidney pie in the British winter tradition. It is hearty, savoury, and built around a flavourful cut. The dish rewards patience and a bit of planning. It tastes better after a night in the fridge before the pastry lid goes on.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
